TY  - JOUR
T1  - Longevity and Lifetime Labor Supply: Evidence and Implications
AU  - Hazan, Moshe
Y1  - 2009/11/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8107
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1829
EP  - 1863
VL  - 77
IS  - 6
KW  - Longevity
KW  - hours worked
KW  - human capital
KW  - economic growth
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8107
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Conventional wisdom suggests that increased life expectancy had a key role in causing a rise in investment in human capital. I incorporate the retirement decision into a version of Ben-Porath's (1967) model and find that a necessary condition for this causal relationship to hold is that increased life expectancy will also increase lifetime labor supply. I then show that this condition does not hold for American men born between 1840 and 1970 and for the American population born between 1890 and 1970. The data suggest similar patterns in Western Europe. I end by discussing the implications of my findings for the debate on the fundamental causes of long-run growth.
ER  - 

